{"lemma":"دِهْلِيزٌ","slug":"دِهْلِيزٌ","root":"د.ه.ل.ز","root_slug":"د-ه-ل-ز","root_link":"/words/roots/د-ه-ل-ز","pos":"N","pos_camel":"noun","paradigm":[],"frequency_in_corpus":0,"cross_references":{"qac":{"found":false},"wiktextract":{"found":true,"entry_count":1,"pos_tags":["noun"],"has_etymology":true,"sense_count":1},"lanes":{"found":true,"entry_ids":["n13282"],"search_url":"https://lanelexicon.com/?s=%D8%AF%D9%90%D9%87%D9%92%D9%84%D9%90%D9%8A%D8%B2%D9%8C"}},"translations":null,"definition":{"source":"wiktextract","senses":[{"pos":"noun","gloss":"corridor; hallway"}]},"etymology":{"source":"wiktextract","text":"From Persian دهلیز (dahliz)."},"ipa":["/dih.liːz/"],"lanes_definition":{"source":"lanes","entries":[{"entry_id":"n13282","headword_ar":"دِهْلِيزٌ","root":"dhlyz","body":[{"kind":"text","text":"["},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"An entrance-passage"},{"kind":"text","text":"of a house;"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"an entrance-hall; a vestibule;"},{"kind":"text","text":"]"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"what is between the"},{"kind":"text","text":"["},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"outer"},{"kind":"text","text":"]"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"door or gate and the house;"},{"kind":"text","text":"(S, K;) the"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"place of entrance to a house:"},{"kind":"text","text":"(Msb:) a Persian word, (S, Msb,) originally"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"dAlyj","text_ar":"داليج"},{"kind":"text","text":", and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"dAlyz","text_ar":"داليز"},{"kind":"text","text":", and"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"dAlAn","text_ar":"دالان"},{"kind":"text","text":", and, as some say,"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"daliyjN","text_ar":"دَلِيجٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":", (Lth,) arabicized: (Lth, S, Msb:) [also, in modern Arabic,"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"an ante-"},{"kind":"page_break","n":925},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"chamber:"},{"kind":"text","text":"and the"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"anterior apartment of a large tent"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"pavilion:"},{"kind":"text","text":"accord. to the MA,"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"a large tent:"},{"kind":"text","text":"accord. to some copies of the K,"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"i. q."},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"jayoy^apN","text_ar":"جَيْيَةٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":": accord. to some,"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"xaniy~apN","text_ar":"خَنِيَّةٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":", which reading is preferred by the author of the TK, who explains"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"dhlyz","text_ar":"دهليز"},{"kind":"text","text":", from the “Burhán,” as meaning “absurd words:” accord. to some,"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Haniy~apN","text_ar":"حَنِيَّةٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":", which I think the right reading, meaning"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"a bowed,"},{"kind":"text","text":"or"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"curved, structure:"},{"kind":"text","text":"Golius seems to have found another reading in the K, namely,"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"Hay~apN","text_ar":"حَيَّةٌ"},{"kind":"text","text":":] pl."},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"dahaAliyzu","text_ar":"دَهَالِيزُ"},{"kind":"text","text":". (S, Msb, K.) ―         -b2-  [Hence,]"},{"kind":"arabic","text_bw":"A^abonaA='u Ald~ahaAliyzi","text_ar":"اَبْنَا=ءُ الدَّهَالِيزِ"},{"kind":"text","text":"(assumed tropical:)"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"Foundlings,"},{"kind":"text","text":"(K, * TA,)"},{"kind":"italic_en","text":"whose fathers are unknown."},{"kind":"text","text":"(TA.) [They are so called because they are generally abandoned at the entrances of mosques or private houses, whence they are usually taken by persons who adopt them.]"}],"source_refs":["Msb","S","Lth"]}]},"classical_definitions":{"source":"hawramani","url":"https://arabiclexicon.hawramani.com/%D8%AF%D9%87%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%B2/","headword_ar":"دهليز","entries":[{"lexicon_id":"dictionary_49","lexicon_en":"Arabic-English Lexicon by Edward William Lane (d. 1876)","lexicon_ar":"المعجم العربي الإنجليزي لإدوارد وليام لين","permalink":"https://arabiclexicon.hawramani.com/?p=60834#2c4785","body_html":"<h3>دهليز</h3><br><br>دِهْلِيزٌ [An entrance-passage of a house; an entrance-hall; a vestibule;] what is between the [outer] door or gate and the house; (<abbr title=\"The Ṣiḥāḥ (of al-Jawharī)\">S</abbr>, <abbr title=\"al-Qāmūs al-Muḥīṭ of Firuzabadi\">K</abbr>;) the place of entrance to a house: (<abbr title=\"The Miṣbāḥ of al-Fayyūmī\">Msb</abbr>:) a Persian word, (<abbr title=\"The Ṣiḥāḥ (of al-Jawharī)\">S</abbr>, <abbr title=\"The Miṣbāḥ of al-Fayyūmī\">Msb</abbr>,) originally داليج, and داليز, and دالان, and, as some say, دَلِيجٌ, (<abbr title=\"El-Leyth Ibn-Nasr Ibn-Seiyar, held by El-Azberee to be the author of the “Eyn,” which he calls “Kitab Leyth” (al-Layth b. Muẓahffar al-Kināni)\">Lth</abbr>,) arabicized: (<abbr title=\"El-Leyth Ibn-Nasr Ibn-Seiyar, held by El-Azberee to be the author of the “Eyn,” which he calls “Kitab Leyth” (al-Layth b. Muẓahffar al-Kināni)\">Lth</abbr>, <abbr title=\"The Ṣiḥāḥ (of al-Jawharī)\">S</abbr>, <abbr title=\"The Miṣbāḥ of al-Fayyūmī\">Msb</abbr>:) [also, in modern Arabic, an ante-chamber: and the anterior apartment of a large tent or pavilion: <abbr title=\"according\">accord.</abbr> to the <abbr title=\"The Muqaddimat al-Adab of al-Zamakhsharī\">MA</abbr>, a large tent: <abbr title=\"according\">accord.</abbr> to some copies of the <abbr title=\"al-Qāmūs al-Muḥīṭ of Firuzabadi\">K</abbr>, <abbr title=\"idem quod (i.e. the same as)\">i. q.</abbr> جَيْئَةٌ: <abbr title=\"according\">accord.</abbr> to some, خَنِيَّةٌ, which reading is preferred by the author of the <abbr title=\"The Turkish translation of al-Qāmūs al-Muḥīṭ of Firuzabadi\">TK</abbr>, who explains دهليز, from the “Burhán,” as meaning “absurd words:”<br><br>accord. to some, حَنِيَّةٌ, which I think the right reading, meaning a bowed, or curved, structure: Golius seems to have found another reading in the <abbr title=\"al-Qāmūs al-Muḥīṭ of Firuzabadi\">K</abbr>, namely, حَيَّةٌ:] <abbr title=\"plural, جَمْعٌ\">pl.</abbr> دَهَالِيزُ. (<abbr title=\"The Ṣiḥāḥ (of al-Jawharī)\">S</abbr>, <abbr title=\"The Miṣbāḥ of al-Fayyūmī\">Msb</abbr>, <abbr title=\"al-Qāmūs al-Muḥīṭ of Firuzabadi\">K</abbr>.) <span class=\"sub-sense\">b2:</span> [Hence,] أَبْنَآءُ الدَّهَالِيزِ (assumed <abbr title=\"مَجَازٌ and مَجَازِيٌّ\">tropical</abbr>:) Foundlings, (<abbr title=\"al-Qāmūs al-Muḥīṭ of Firuzabadi\">K</abbr>, * <abbr title=\"The Tāj al-ʿArūs of Sayyid Murtaḍā al-Zabīdī\">TA</abbr>,) whose fathers are unknown. (<abbr title=\"The Tāj al-ʿArūs of Sayyid Murtaḍā al-Zabīdī\">TA</abbr>.) [They are so called because they are generally abandoned at the entrances of mosques or private houses, whence they are usually taken by persons who adopt them.]"}]}}